{
  "text": "Are such biases also present in lateral prefrontal cortex? Research in non-human primates has demonstrated that retinotopic biases also extend into the VLPFC. For example, near the face-selective cells reported by O 'Scalaidhe et al. (1997) ; [CITATION_1] , previous studies have reported neurons with foveal biases [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, it has been reported (O 'Scalaidhe et al., 1997; [CITATION_3] ) that a subset of faceselective cells in monkeys responded strongest to stimuli presented in the fovea, and weakly to stimuli presented in the periphery with weakest responses to peripheral presentations of spots of light. While peripherally presented faces only elicited very weak responses, these responses were still stronger than the responses to peripherally presented spots of light.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "7097688",
    "[CITATION_2]": "23779265",
